Distributed Web Infrastructure

Diagram

User → DNS (www.foobar.com
) → HAProxy Load Balancer →
Nginx Server 1 / Nginx Server 2 →
Application Server 1 / Application Server 2 →
MySQL Primary → MySQL Replica

Purpose of each component
- Load balancer: spreads incoming requests across multiple servers, improving availability and handling more traffic.
- Two web/application servers: ensure redundancy and share the workload, so the system keeps running even if one server fails.
- Primary-replica database: provides a main database for writes and a secondary copy for backup and read operations.

Load balancing
- Algorithm: Round Robin.
- How it works: incoming requests are distributed sequentially across servers in a continuous loop, ensuring balanced usage.

Cluster mode
- This setup uses an active-active configuration, where both servers handle requests simultaneously.
- In active-active, all nodes are operational and serve traffic.
- In contrast, active-passive has one active node while the other remains idle until a failure occurs.

Database replication
- The primary node processes all write operations.
- The replica node continuously synchronizes data from the primary and can handle read requests or serve as a backup.
- Typically, the application sends writes to the primary and may distribute read queries depending on the architecture.

Limitations and issues
- The load balancer can still be a single point of failure if there is only one instance.
- Absence of a firewall exposes the system to potential security threats.
- Lack of HTTPS means data is transmitted without encryption.
- Without monitoring, system failures and performance degradation may not be detected promptly.